Here's how to implement all three requirements:

**1 & 2. Guard navigation with a confirmation dialog in `AppShell.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop &&
        Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page &&
        page.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

Key points:
- `GetDeferral()` is required for async checks — without it the navigation completes before your `await` returns.
- `args.Cancel()` stops the navigation if the user chooses "Stay".

**3. Custom "Cancel" back button in `EditProductPage.xaml`:**

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

```csharp
// In your ViewModel or code-behind
[RelayCommand]
async Task Back()
{
    // This triggers OnNavigating, so the guard still fires
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

The `BackButtonBehavior.Command` intercepts the button tap, letting you route it through `GoToAsync("..")` which then hits your `OnNavigating` guard. This gives you a single confirmation path whether the user taps your "Cancel" button or uses a swipe-back gesture.
